The price per kilogram for ghee in both the organized and unorganized segments is expected to rise from ₹ 466 per kilogram and ₹ 436 per kilogram in 2015, respectively, to ₹ 726 per kilogram and ₹ 679 per kilogram in 2020, respectively.

South India represents the largest market for ghee in India accounting for 26.6% of the total ghee market, followed by north India (26.5%), east India (24.3%) and west India (22.6%). Within the organized segment, Amul, the Karnataka Milk Federation and SMC Foods Limited (Madhusudan ghee) accounted for 15%, 11% and 9%, respectively, of total ghee sold in the organized segment. Other major players in the organized segment of the ghee market include Rajasthan Cooperative Dairy Federation Limited, Sterling Agro Industries Limited (“Sterling Agro”), Bholey Baba Dairy and our Company. While companies like Amul and our Company mainly cater to the retail segment, companies like SMC Foods Limited, Bholey Baba Dairy and VRS Foods mainly cater to the bulk segment.

